00:13:06.140 --> 00:13:09.810
So black abolitionists like Frederick Douglass,
Henry Highland Garnett and apparently David

00:13:09.810 --> 00:13:14.400
Walker were the most eloquent spokesmen for
the ideal of equal citizenship in the United

00:13:14.400 --> 00:13:16.029
States for black and white people.

00:13:16.029 --> 00:13:18.040
In his 1852 Independence Day Address.

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:21.930
By the way, international viewers, our Independence
Day is July 4th, so he gave this speech on

00:13:21.930 --> 00:13:23.020
July 4th.

00:13:23.020 --> 00:13:25.970
Frederick Douglass said:
“Would you argue with me that man is entitled

00:13:25.970 --> 00:13:26.970
to liberty?

00:13:26.970 --> 00:13:29.269
That he is the rightful owner of his own body?

00:13:29.269 --> 00:13:30.790
You have already declared it.

00:13:30.790 --> 00:13:33.350
Must I argue the wrongfulness of slavery?

00:13:33.350 --> 00:13:37.370
… There is not a man beneath the canopy
of heaven that does not know that slavery

00:13:37.370 --> 00:13:38.820
is wrong for him.”

00:13:38.820 --> 00:13:43.310
And in the end, the sophistication and elegance
of the black abolitionists’ arguments became

00:13:43.310 --> 00:13:45.780
one of the strongest arguments for abolition.

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:50.430
If black people were better off enslaved,
and inherently inferior, how could anyone

00:13:50.430 --> 00:13:52.579
account for a man like Frederick Douglass?

00:13:52.579 --> 00:13:56.420
Abolitionism—at least until after the Civil
War—pushed all other reform movements to

00:13:56.420 --> 00:13:57.420
the edges.

00:13:57.420 --> 00:14:00.620
